Data Gathering¶

Importation of Python Libraries¶

In [1]:
# importing necessary python libaries for this project
import pandas as pd # to work with pandas dataframe
import numpy as np
import json  # to work with json data
from timeit import default_timer as timer # this is to enable the timing of the code
import requests # helps download url contents programmatically
import tweepy # helps work with the twitter API
from tweepy import OAuthHandler
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup # helps scrape data from websites

Loading 'WeRateDogs' Twitter archive data¶

  1. Direct download of the WeRateDogs Twitter archive data (twitter_archive_enhanced.csv)
In [2]:
# this is to read the 'twitter_archive_enhanced.csv' file,this contains tweet_ids from the original dataset.
Twitter_archive = pd.read_csv('twitter-archive-enhanced.csv')
  1. Using the Requests library to download the tweet image prediction (image_predictions.tsv)
In [3]:
# get the url
url = 'https://d17h27t6h515a5.cloudfront.net/topher/2017/August/599fd2ad_image-predictions/image-predictions.tsv'
response = requests.get(url)

# this is to write the content of url to a file
Image_predictions = 'image_predictions.tsv'
with open(Image_predictions, mode='wb') as tsv_file:
    tsv_file.write(response.content)

# this is to read the'image_predictions.tsv' file,this contains tweet_ids from the original dataset.

  1. Use the Tweepy library to query additional data via the Twitter API (tweet_json.txt)
In [6]:
# connect to the api and initialize API

# for this next block, insert your own key, token and secrets
consumer_key = ''
consumer_secret = ''
access_token = ''
access_secret = ''

# create an authorization using the consumer key and secret
auth = tweepy.OAuthHandler(consumer_key, consumer_secret)
# set access uding your access token and secret
auth.set_access_token(access_token, access_secret)

#call the API
api = tweepy.API(auth, wait_on_rate_limit = True)

Query Twitter's API for JSON data for each tweet ID in the Twitter archive

In [12]:
# initialize a counter to help track progress
count = 0

# create a dictionary to store the tweet ids that cannot be retrieved
fails_dict = {}

# start tracking the time taken to run the next lines of code
start = timer()

# Each tweet's returned JSON to be saved as a new line in a .txt file

# open the text file in write mode
with open('tweet_json.txt', 'w') as outfile:
# This loop will likely take 20-30 minutes to run because of Twitter's rate limit
    for tweet_id in tweet_ids:
        # Each tweet that's being queried is to be increased by 1with counter  
        count += 1
        # this is to print the number and tweet id
        print(str(count) + ": " + str(tweet_id))
        try:
            # to get the status of the tweet
            tweet = api.get_status(tweet_id, tweet_mode='extended')
            print("Success")
            json.dump(tweet._json, outfile)  # to write the json data to the text file opened
            outfile.write('\n')  # to write each tweet on a new line 
        except tweepy.TweepError as e:
            print("Fail")
            # write the tweet id that failed along with the error message to the fails_dict dictionary
            fails_dict[tweet_id] = e
            pass
end = timer()
print(end - start)
print(fails_dict)

Reading the data from the tweet_json.txt file into a dataframe¶

In [6]:
#create a dictionary
dic_json=[]
# opening the file in read mode
with open('tweet_json.txt','r') as json_input_file:
     # using 'for loop' to loop through each line in the file
    for tweet_id in json_input_file:
        
# using json.loads() method to convert the json string to a python dictionary        
        variable = json.loads(tweet_id)
    # extraction of variables for dataframe
        tweet_id = variable["id"]
        retweet_count = variable['retweet_count']
        favorite_count = variable['favorite_count']
        
        # appending variables to dictionary 'dic_json'
        dic_json.append({'tweet_id':tweet_id,
                        'retweet_count': retweet_count,'favorite_count':favorite_count})
json.txt_table = pd.DataFrame(dic_json, columns = ['tweet_id','retweet_count','favorite_count'])

Quality issues¶

  1. Data in the 'image_prediction' and 'json.txt_table' table is incomplete.

  2. 'Twitter_archive' - missing values in in_reply_to_status_id, in_reply_to_user_id and expanded_urls columns.

  3. 'Twitter_archive' - Errorneous datatype1 (timestamp)

  4. 'Twitter_archive' - source column contains invalid data.

  5. 'Twitter_archive' - some rows in expanded_urls column has more than one links combined together.

  6. 'image_prediction' - p1,p2,p3 columns have names of dog breeds are inconsistent.

  7. 'Twitter_archive' - some words like "a", "an","such", "the" "quite", "None" was wrongly inputed as dog name

  8. 'Twitter_archive' - None value for dog stage in the doggo, floofer, pupper, puppo column.

Tidiness issues¶

  1. A single table is needed from the three tables.

  2. Twitter_archive table should have dog stage variables (doggo, floofer, pupper, puppo)columns as a single column.

  3. 'NAN' value only in retweeted_status_id retweeted_status_user_id, retweeted_status_timestamp column in the Twitter_archive Table

Cleaning Data¶

Issue 4: Source Column Invalid Data¶

Define:¶

Code¶

In [31]:
# assign variable to the parttern for which the url is to be extracted
valid_links = r'(https?:\/\/(?:www\.)?[-a-zA-Z0-9@:%._+~#=]{1,256}\.[a-zA-Z0-9()]{1,6}[-a-zA-Z0-9()@:%_+.~#?&/=]*)'
# this is to extract the url from the column
Twitter_archive_cl['Source'] = Twitter_archive_cl['source'].str.extract(valid_links, expand=True)
# drop the dirty(source)column
Twitter_archive_cl.drop(['source'],axis = 1, inplace = True)

Issue 2: Twitter_archive - Multiple Column¶

Define:¶

  • The four Dog stage column is to be represented by a single column by concatenation

Code¶

In [44]:
# Making all NaN in each dog stage column empty
w = Twitter_archive_cl['doggo'].replace(np.nan,'')
x = Twitter_archive_cl['floofer'].replace(np.nan,'')
y = Twitter_archive_cl['pupper'].replace(np.nan,'')
z = Twitter_archive_cl['puppo'].replace(np.nan,'')
# This is to create a dog_stage column using concatenation
Twitter_archive_cl['dog_stage'] = w + x + y + z
# this for case where some dogs has two stages
Twitter_archive_cl['dog_stage'] = Twitter_archive_cl['dog_stage'].replace({'':np.nan,'doggopupper':'doggo,pupper','doggopuppo':'doggo,puppo','doggofloofer':'doggo,floofer'})
# this to drop the doggo, floofer, pupper, puppo
Twitter_archive_cl.drop(['doggo','pupper','puppo','floofer'],axis = 1, inplace = True)

What algorithm prediction has the most accurate prediction of dog breeds?¶

In [54]:

Out[54]:
True     1477
False    517 
Name: p1_dog, dtype: int64
In [55]:
Twitter_archive_m['p2_dog'].value_counts()
Out[55]:
True     1495
False    499 
Name: p2_dog, dtype: int64
In [56]:
Twitter_archive_m['p3_dog'].value_counts()
Out[56]:
True     1446
False    548 
Name: p3_dog, dtype: int64

The code above returns the "True"and 'False' value of the algorithm, looking at the value it was observed that p2 algorithm has a higher prediction of the breed of dog in the tweet images, this makes it more effective than p1 and p3. Also, for 25% of the tweets and below, p2 has a confidence of 0.00000001 which happens to be its minimum, 0.4880140 to be the maximun and a mean of 0.1344195. p2 has a lesser confidence when compaired with p1 an higher confidence when compaired with p3.

What is the dog stage distribution?¶

In [57]:
# This is to display the values of each dog stage
Twitter_archive_m['dog_stage'].value_counts()
Out[57]:
pupper           203
doggo            63 
puppo            22 
doggo,pupper     9  
floofer          7  
doggo,puppo      1  
doggo,floofer    1  
Name: dog_stage, dtype: int64

Pupper has the most occurence dog stage followed by doggo and puppo. It was also observed that some dogs have two stage such as doggo, pupper with 9 occurence floofer coming after it with 7 occurrence. Lastly we have doggo , floofer and doggo, puppo being the least occurence with 1 as value.

Visualization of Dog Stage Distribution¶

In [58]:
# this is to plot the visual of the Dog Stage Distribution
Twitter_archive_m['dog_stage'].value_counts().plot(kind='bar',figsize=(8,8));
plt.xlabel('Dog Stage')
plt.ylabel('Level of Occurence')
plt.title('Visualization of Dog Stage Distribution')
Out[58]:
Text(0.5,1,'Visualization of Dog Stage Distribution')

Pupper has the highest level of occurrence of over 200 followed by doggo with over 50, puppo over 25, doggo,pupper and floofer below 25 while doggo, floofer and doggo, puppo being the least occurrence.
